quran[7]{c,v,t,f}:
  6,125,"Whomever Allah wants to guide, He expands his chest to<i class=""s"">(accept) </i>Islam; and whomever He wants to lead astray, He makes his chest tight, <span class=",footnotes:1:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Nafie’, Shu’ba and Abu Ja’far read it as: “…He makes his chest tight, very constricted,”</span>,footnotes:2:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ibn Kathir read it as: “as though he were ascending in the sky.”Shu’ba read it as: “…as though he were ascending on and on in the sky.”</span>
  6,126,"And this is your Lord’s path, straight. We{1}have surely detailed the signs for people who constantly remember.",footnotes:1:A grammatical shift from 3rd person to 1st person.
  6,127,"For them is the Home of Peace with their Lord, and He is their Ultimate Guardian on account of what they used to do."
  6,128,"Thus on the day <span class=",footnotes:1:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: All except for Hafs and Rouh read it as: “…We herd them…”</span>,footnotes:2:The Arabic word used is <i>jinn</i> which are unseen beings that are accountable for their actions.,footnotes:3:Frequently the Qur’an addresses the events of the Hereafter in past tense; this grammatical shift should be pondered by the reader.
  6,129,"And thus We make the unjust allies of one another on account of what they used to earn."
  6,130,"“O assembly of unseen beings<a class=""sup""><sup>b </sup></a>and humans, did there not come to you messengers from among you, relating to you My signs and warning you of the meeting of this day of yours?” They said, “We have<i class=""s"">(now) </i>testified against ourselves.” And the Earlier Life deceived them, and they testified against themselves that they were deniers.",footnotes:1:The Arabic word used is <i>jinn</i> which are unseen beings that are accountable for their actions.
  6,131,"That is because your<a class=""sup""><sup>sg </sup></a>Lord would never destroy towns unjustly while their inhabitants are oblivious."
